	<h2>Laundry Operations</h2>
	<p>In-unit laundry is a luxury rarely found in short-term sublets. You will rely on local laundromats. There are two primary execution methods.</p>
	
	<h3>Wash and Fold Services</h3>
	<p>Most laundromats offer drop-off "wash and fold" services priced per pound. You drop off dirty laundry in the morning and pick it up clean and folded the next day. The average cost is $1.25 to $1.75 per pound. This saves three hours of your weekend and is highly recommended for interns working 60-hour weeks.</p>
	
	<h3>Self-Service</h3>
	<p>Self-service requires loading quarters or a prepaid card into machines. You must remain on-site or nearby to move clothes from the washer to the dryer promptly. Leaving clothes unattended risks theft or having your wet clothes removed by a waiting customer.</p>

	<h2>Grocery Procurement</h2>
	<p>Transporting groceries in Manhattan requires carrying bags blocks at a time or navigating crowded subways. You must adapt your purchasing habits.</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li><strong>High-Frequency, Low-Volume:</strong> Stop buying two weeks of groceries at once. Buy what you can comfortably carry in two reusable bags every few days.</li>
		<li><strong>Bodegas and Corner Stores:</strong> Use local bodegas for immediate needs like milk, eggs, or single-roll paper towels. Prices are higher, but the convenience offsets the premium.</li>
		<li><strong>Delivery Infrastructure:</strong> Utilize Amazon Fresh, FreshDirect, or Whole Foods delivery for heavy items like liquids and bulk goods. Delivery fees are justified by the physical toll saved.</li>
	</ul>
</InternWiki>
